I read the draft on the forums - sorry I didn't get to comment in time.

I quite like the angle you have, but I think it could use more substance and elucidation. kaktus' suggestions are very good, so I have just two others to add:

1) As well as being petty, the EC members here don't come across as very *creative*. The arguments are limited to , without much in the way of nuance. Why does no-one consider trying to supply food, but without revealing its source? What about revealing the source, and planning to amnesticize anyone from the Russian government once they're done? Does 80,000 cans per day actually make an appreciable difference to the famine? If the city falls, Adolf Hitler might get his hands on an unlimited supply of free food. Should that not be taken into consideration? Does revealing it to the Soviets make it more likely that Hitler will find out about it, if he does capture Leningrad?

You obviously don't need to flesh out all of these factors, but unless the angle is that the EC is so inhumane that they don't bother to think at all (and I didn't get that sense from the text), then it would help to make this more of a real debate, and less of a sketch.

2) I didn't find the initial call-in excerpts terribly convincing. While they are dramatic, I wondered at the realism of both the language (is the equivalent of  a commonly used profanity in Russian?) and the people who call in to a government help line to confess to crimes and reveal their opposition to a totalitarian regime. That could be made a lot more believable.

As an aside, this might be one situation where having a level of security over the Addendum is justified - I can't imagine the Foundation wants just anyone seeing how petty the EC acts (even if some way in the past).







