Tentative upvote. The core concept ( that being said, I feel like this article ought to have either been significantly longer or significantly shorter. Some thoughts:

+block

–block


Some of the recordings are great, but their usage here felt a bit out of place. Also, although I quite liked the inner squabbling of the EC (the antagonism between E-5 and E-2 over Nanking vs Leningrad felt credible, to me), the lack of discussion over alternative solutions made the proceedings feel flat. I understand that there's probably a good reason they can't distribute the cans anonymously, or amnesticize government officials afterward  but the fact that no one even brings it up made it feel less credible.

One thing that came up that I liked: Mentioning the political fallout of discovery. I think this in particular is how you sell the opposition as having a credible point. Yes, we can amnesticize officials; yes, we can distribute food anonymously. But what if GRU P notices? Maybe not all records of SCP-3554's existence were destroyed. Maybe they know something about a food-producing anomaly that's been lost, and a sudden surplus of borscht  they're going to notice if Leningrad doesn't starve. And maybe the Foundation can't afford to have GRU P sniffing around.

Then the conversation becomes less 'we have to hide anomalies at all costs' and more 'what's the consequence of having GRU P discover we're hiding anomalies from them right under their own noses?'. That, to me, is a far more interesting discussion  and losing it could be catastrophic for the Foundation as an organization.

Either way, I feel like this would have worked better if we either 1) Never got to see the conversation where they condemned Leningrad to starve, or 2) Saw that conversation expanded and more focused on why letting Leningrad starve might be the Foundation's only politically viable option.

That being said, it's always fun and neat to see skips focused both on history and ethics, so  tentative +1.










