+1. This article deserves way more attention.

Regarding :

+block

–block


The question of nuance is kind of a non-issue for me. The Foundation is talking about whether or not to expose SCP-3554 to the ChD AKN because that's what Bessonov requested. It's an all or nothing issue because that's what the request at hand is. The Foundation deals in anomalous phenomena.

The question of whether or not the Foundation can aid Leningrad using SCP-3554 without exposing SCP-3554 has undoubtedly been considered by both Bessonov (who is the one making the request in the first place) and the Ethics Committee. It's difficult to imagine the Foundation could even attempt this without ChD AKN/GRU  becoming aware that, for example, tens of thousands of civilians had gotten food supplies from a source they could not remember or identify, and then proceeding to investigate. The conversation between the EC members states that this is the last day they have to vote on this issue, implying previous, more nuanced conversations have taken place. My disbelief is sufficiently suspended.

The question of whether the Ethics Committee should be more  strategies designed by a committee whose purpose has never been to strategize anything, but to review  the ethics of existing or proposed strategies.

The question of whether or not the Foundation should design and enact a non-anomalous humanitarian program is an entirely separate issue that doesn't generally fall under the Foundation's purview. There's no real precedent for such a thing on this site in general, so I don't expect this article to start it.




Airtight for me. Love it.





